# Problem Explanation
---
### Problem Interpretation

#### Physical System Description
The problem deals with a weakly coupled, quasi-neutral plasma composed of electrons and singly charged positive ions (“+1” ions).  
• In equilibrium the particle number densities follow Boltzmann distributions and the plasma exhibits Debye shielding.  
• A single test point charge can be inserted into this plasma to probe the electro-static potential distribution.  
• Various dynamical situations are considered:  
  1. One-dimensional momentum balance of each species in the presence of an electric field.  
  2. Three-dimensional, steady-state shielding of a point charge (Debye shielding).  
  3. Force balance of a flowing ion population in an external magnetic field with a non-uniform electric field.  
  4.–7. Small-amplitude wave perturbations (sound-wave frequency range) in an un-magnetised plasma, analysed through the continuity, momentum, energy (adiabatic) equations and Poisson’s equation, with subsequent special limits that lead to various dispersion relations.

#### Variables and Parameters
n_j  number density of species j (j = i for ions, e for electrons)  
n_{j0} equilibrium (unperturbed) number density of species j  
n_0  common equilibrium number density when quasi-neutral (n_{i0} = n_{e0} = n_0)  
Δn  difference between ion and electron densities, Δn = n_i − n_e  
m_j  mass of species j  
q_j  charge of species j (q_e = −e, q_i = +e)  
e   elementary charge magnitude (1.602 × 10⁻¹⁹ C)  
T_j  absolute temperature of species j  
k_B  Boltzmann constant  
φ  electro-static potential  
E  electric-field strength (vector, but written as E or its x-component where 1-D)  
p_j  pressure of species j  
v_j  macroscopic (bulk) velocity of species j  
γ_j  adiabatic index (ratio of specific heats) of species j  
r  distance from the test charge to the field point in 3-D space  
λ_D Debye shielding length, defined as λ_D ≡ −φ r / (d(φ r)/dr)  
λ_{De} electron Debye length (ion temperature → ∞ limit)  
L  characteristic scale length of the electric-field gradient (E / (dE/dx))  
ω_0 characteristic angular frequency of the macroscopic motion, approximately v_i / L  
ω_{pe} electron plasma frequency, ω_{pe} = √(e² n_0 / (ε₀ m_e))  
ω_{ce} electron cyclotron frequency, ω_{ce} = e B / m_e  
B  external magnetic-field strength (vector magnitude given)  
ω  angular frequency of a small perturbation (wave)  
k  wave-number of the perturbation (assumed along x-direction)  
v_g  group velocity of a wave  
ε₀  permittivity of free space (8.854 × 10⁻¹² F m⁻¹)

Numerical constants supplied for evaluation tasks:  
n_0 = 1.0 × 10²⁰ m⁻³, k_B T_e = 10 keV, k_B T_i = 1 keV, B = 1 T, ω_0 / (2π) = 1 GHz, e and ε₀ as above.

Perturbation notation: subscript 1 denotes first-order (small) disturbance quantities, subscript 0 denotes equilibrium quantities.

#### Initial Conditions
• Equilibrium state: spatially uniform densities (n_{i0}, n_{e0} = n_0), uniform temperatures T_i, T_e, and no macroscopic flow (v_{j0} = 0) unless otherwise specified (e.g., ion drift v_i with external B in part 3).  
• For wave analysis (parts 4–7): the plasma is initially at rest and uniform in free space; small perturbations of the form exp(−i ω t + i k x) are imposed.

#### Constraints and Assumptions
1. Weak-coupling (small-potential) condition: |q_j φ| ≪ k_B T_j, i.e., q_j φ / (k_B T_j) ≪ 1.  
2. Quasi-neutrality (when invoked): n_{i0} = n_{e0} = n_0; but departures Δn may be considered on Debye scales or under force balance with flow and magnetic field.  
3. Ions are singly charged (+e).  
4. For parts 4–7 the plasma is un-magnetised (B = 0) unless otherwise noted; in part 3 the magnetic field is present.  
5. One-dimensional spatial variation (x-direction) is adopted for momentum and wave equations unless explicitly treating the 3-D point-charge problem.  
6. Pressure gradients can be neglected for ions in part 3 (force balance section).  
7. Adiabatic processes with fixed γ_j are assumed for pressure evolution in the wave analysis.  
8. Retention of only first-order terms in perturbation quantities when linearising the governing equations for wave analysis.  
9. When deriving λ_{De}, the electron-only shielding limit corresponds to T_i → ∞ (ions assumed immobile for shielding scale).  
10. Group velocity definition pertains to the dispersion relation obtained in part 6.

#### Solution Objective
The problem asks for a series of demonstrations, derivations, or numerical evaluations:

(1) Show that, in equilibrium, electrons obey the Boltzmann distribution starting from the one-dimensional momentum equation (electron temperature uniform and time-independent).  

(2) With a test charge q inserted:  
  2.1 Determine the steady-state electro-static potential φ(r) in 3-D space.  
  2.2 Obtain the characteristic shielding length λ_D from φ(r) and write explicit expressions for λ_D and the electron Debye length λ_{De}.  
  2.3 Using given numerical data, produce the numerical value of λ_D.

(3) Express the relative charge imbalance Δn / n under ion flow and an external magnetic field, in terms of ω_{pe}, ω_{ce}, and ω_0; then estimate Δn / n using the supplied numerical values.

(4) Linearise the governing equations for small perturbations in an un-magnetised, initially uniform plasma and derive a general relation (dispersion equation) connecting ω and k, expressed via ω, k, γ_j, m_j, T_j, λ_{De}, and k_B.

(5) From that general relation, extract the leading-order dispersion relation when ω² and k² k_B T_e / m_i are of comparable magnitude (T_e ~ T_i), and specify the condition under which it reduces to the classical ion-acoustic dispersion ω² = k² (γ_e k_B T_e + γ_i k_B T_i) / m_i.

(6) For the regime where ω² is comparable to k² k_B T_e / m_e (T_e ~ T_i), provide the leading-order simplified dispersion relation and the corresponding group velocity v_g expressed in terms of ω_{pe}² and other known quantities.

(7) Assuming electrons follow the Boltzmann distribution (weak-coupling) and enforcing quasi-neutrality (n_i = n_e) while retaining the ion equations, derive the ion-acoustic dispersion relation under these conditions and explain how it can be obtained from the classical ion-acoustic relation referenced in part (5).

No explicit algebraic solutions, derivations, or numerical calculations are to be performed here; only the structure, definitions, and objectives have been summarised.

# Solution
---
# Refined Solution

### Step 1  
\[\boxed{m_{j}n_{j}\left(\partial_{t}v_{j}+v_{j}\partial_{x}v_{j}\right)=q_{j}n_{j}E-\partial_{x}p_{j}}\]  
\[\boxed{E=-\partial_{x}\phi}\]  
\[\boxed{p_{e}=n_{e}k_{B}T_{e}\;(\text{isothermal electrons,\; }T_{e}=\text{const.})}\]

\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Equilibrium (static, }v_{e}=0,\;\partial_{t}v_{e}=0)\!: \nonumber\\
0 &= q_{e}n_{e}E-\partial_{x}p_{e} 
     = -e n_{e}\left(-\partial_{x}\phi\right) - \partial_{x}(n_{e}k_{B}T_{e}) \label{eq1:momentum}\tag{1}\\
\Rightarrow\;&\frac{\partial_{x}n_{e}}{n_{e}}
           =\frac{e}{k_{B}T_{e}}\partial_{x}\phi. \label{eq1:dln}\tag{2}\\
&\text{Integrate both sides:}\nonumber\\
\ln n_{e} &=\frac{e\phi}{k_{B}T_{e}}+C \label{eq1:int}\tag{3}\\
\Rightarrow\; n_{e} &= n_{0}\exp\!\left(\frac{e\phi}{k_{B}T_{e}}\right), \label{eq1:Boltz}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

showing that electrons satisfy the Boltzmann distribution in equilibrium.

### Step 2  
\[\boxed{n_{j}=n_{0}\exp\!\Bigl(-\dfrac{q_{j}\phi}{k_{B}T_{j}}\Bigr)}\]  
\[\boxed{\left|\dfrac{q_{j}\phi}{k_{B}T_{j}}\right|\ll1\;(\text{weak coupling})}\]

\[
\begin{align}
n_{i}&\simeq n_{0}\!\left(1-\frac{e\phi}{k_{B}T_{i}}\right), &
n_{e}&\simeq n_{0}\!\left(1+\frac{e\phi}{k_{B}T_{e}}\right),\\
\Rightarrow\;
n_{i}-n_{e} &=-n_{0}\frac{e\phi}{k_{B}}\left(\frac{1}{T_{i}}+\frac{1}{T_{e}}\right).
\label{eq2:delta_n}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3  
\[\boxed{\nabla^{2}\phi=-\dfrac{1}{\varepsilon_{0}}\Bigl[q\delta(\mathbf r)+e\,(n_{i}-n_{e})\Bigr]}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\nabla^{2}\phi &=-\frac{q}{\varepsilon_{0}}\delta(\mathbf r)
                +\frac{n_{0}e^{2}}{\varepsilon_{0}k_{B}}
                 \left(\frac{1}{T_{e}}+\frac{1}{T_{i}}\right)\phi \nonumber\\
              &\equiv -\frac{q}{\varepsilon_{0}}\delta(\mathbf r)+\frac{\phi}{\lambda_{D}^{2}},
\label{eq3:Poisson}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]
defining the Debye length

\[
\boxed{\lambda_{D}^{2}
       =\frac{\varepsilon_{0}k_{B}}
             {n_{0}e^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{T_{e}}+\frac{1}{T_{i}}\right)^{-1}} \label{eq3:lambdaD}\tag{7}
\]

### Step 4  
\[\boxed{\left(\nabla^{2}-\lambda_{D}^{-2}\right)\phi=-\dfrac{q}{\varepsilon_{0}}\delta(\mathbf r)}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\text{Green-function solution in 3-D:}\quad
\phi(r)=\frac{q}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\frac{e^{-r/\lambda_{D}}}{r},\qquad r>0.
\label{eq4:phi}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5  
\[\boxed{\lambda_{De}=\sqrt{\dfrac{\varepsilon_{0}k_{B}T_{e}}{n_{0}e^{2}}}},\qquad
\boxed{\lambda_{Di}=\sqrt{\dfrac{\varepsilon_{0}k_{B}T_{i}}{n_{0}e^{2}}}}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\lambda_{D}^{-2}&=\lambda_{De}^{-2}+\lambda_{Di}^{-2}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\boxed{\lambda_{D}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\lambda_{De}^{-2}+\lambda_{Di}^{-2}}}}.
\label{eq5:lambda_sum}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 6 (Numerical evaluation – corrected)  
\[
\boxed{
\begin{aligned}
&n_{0}=1.0\times10^{20}\,\mathrm{m}^{-3},\;
\varepsilon_{0}=8.854\times10^{-12}\,\mathrm{F\,m^{-1}},\\
&k_{B}T_{e}=10\,\text{keV}=1.602\times10^{-15}\,\text{J},\\
&k_{B}T_{i}= 1\,\text{keV}=1.602\times10^{-16}\,\text{J},\\
&e=1.602\times10^{-19}\,\text{C}
\end{aligned}}
\]

\[
\begin{align}
\lambda_{De}&=\sqrt{\frac{(8.854\times10^{-12})(1.602\times10^{-15})}
                          {(1.0\times10^{20})(1.602\times10^{-19})^{2}}}
             \approx 7.4\times10^{-5}\,\text{m},\label{eq6:lDe}\tag{10}\\[6pt]
\lambda_{Di}&=\sqrt{\frac{(8.854\times10^{-12})(1.602\times10^{-16})}
                          {(1.0\times10^{20})(1.602\times10^{-19})^{2}}}
             \approx 2.3\times10^{-5}\,\text{m},\label{eq6:lDi}\tag{11}\\[6pt]
\lambda_{D}&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\lambda_{De}^{-2}+\lambda_{Di}^{-2}}}
           \approx 2.2\times10^{-5}\,\text{m}\;(22\;\mu\text{m}).\label{eq6:lD}\tag{12}
\end{align}
\]
(The earlier erroneous value \(2.3\times10^{-4}\,\text{m}\) for \(\lambda_{Di}\) has been corrected to \(2.3\times10^{-5}\,\text{m}\).)

### Step 7  
\[\boxed{\mathbf 0=e\bigl(\mathbf E+\mathbf v_{i}\!\times\!\mathbf B\bigr)}\]  
\[\boxed{\nabla\!\cdot\!\mathbf E=\dfrac{e\,\Delta n}{\varepsilon_{0}}}\]  
\[\boxed{\omega_{0}\approx\frac{v_{i}}{L}},\;
  \boxed{\omega_{ce}=\frac{eB}{m_{e}}},\;
  \boxed{\omega_{pe}^{2}=\frac{e^{2}n_{0}}{\varepsilon_{0}m_{e}}}\]

\[
\begin{align}
|E|&=v_{i}B,\qquad 
|\nabla E|\simeq\frac{E}{L}=\omega_{0}B,\\
\frac{e\,\Delta n}{\varepsilon_{0}}&\simeq\omega_{0}B
\;\Rightarrow\;
\frac{\Delta n}{n_{0}}=\frac{\omega_{0}\,\omega_{ce}}{\omega_{pe}^{2}}.
\label{eq7:deltan}\tag{13}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 8  
\[
\boxed{\omega_{0}=2\pi(1\,\text{GHz})=6.28\times10^{9}\,\text{s}^{-1}},\;
\boxed{B=1\,\text{T}},\;
\boxed{\omega_{ce}=1.76\times10^{11}\,\text{s}^{-1}},\;
\boxed{\omega_{pe}=5.64\times10^{11}\,\text{s}^{-1}}
\]

\[
\begin{align}
\frac{\Delta n}{n}
&=\frac{(6.28\times10^{9})(1.76\times10^{11})}{(5.64\times10^{11})^{2}}
\approx 3.5\times10^{-3}.
\label{eq8:deltan_num}\tag{14}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 9  
\[\boxed{\partial_{t}n_{j}+\partial_{x}(n_{j}v_{j})=0}\]  
\[\boxed{m_{j}n_{j}\left(\partial_{t}v_{j}+v_{j}\partial_{x}v_{j}\right)=q_{j}n_{j}E-\partial_{x}p_{j}}\]  
\[\boxed{(\partial_{t}+v_{j}\partial_{x})(p_{j}n_{j}^{-\gamma_{j}})=0
\Rightarrow p_{j1}=\gamma_{j}k_{B}T_{j}n_{j1}}\]  
